VALUES
-- Starting a Broker (6)
('forex-regulation-worldwide-2025', 'Forex Regulation Around the World: 2025 Overview', 'Overview of regulatory regimes for forex activities across key jurisdictions: EU, UK, Asia, and offshore territories.', '<h2>European Regulation: MiFID II and Beyond</h2><p>The European Union maintains one of the strictest regulatory environments for forex brokers through MiFID II. Key requirements include maximum leverage limits of 1:30 for major pairs, negative balance protection, and mandatory risk warnings. CySEC in Cyprus remains the most popular EU regulator for forex brokers, offering a balance between regulatory rigor and business flexibility.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771985/pexels-photo-6771985.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Forex Regulation" /><h2>Asia-Pacific and UK</h2><p>The FCA in the UK enforces some of the toughest standards globally, with capital requirements exceeding 730,000 EUR for market makers. ASIC in Australia has tightened rules significantly since 2021. Japan''s JFSA permits leverage up to 1:25, while Singapore''s MAS requires minimum capital of S$1 million for capital markets services licenses.</p><h2>Offshore Jurisdictions</h2><p>Offshore regulators like Vanuatu (VFSC), Belize (IFSC), and the Seychelles (FSA) offer faster licensing with lower capital requirements. While these licenses provide legal frameworks, they carry less credibility with sophisticated clients. Many brokers use a dual-licensing strategy: offshore for flexible conditions and EU/UK licenses for trust and reputation.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771985/pexels-photo-6771985.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['regulation', 'MiFID II', 'FCA', 'ASIC', 'license', 'forex', 'compliance'], 9, 'Forex Regulation Worldwide: 2025', 'Overview of forex regulatory regimes worldwide. EU, UK, Asia, and offshore jurisdictions.', true, now()),

('marketing-strategy-new-forex-broker', 'Marketing Strategy for a New Forex Broker', 'Effective channels for attracting traders to a new brokerage: SEO, contextual advertising, affiliate marketing, and social media.', '<h2>Digital Marketing Foundation</h2><p>New brokers must establish digital presence across multiple channels simultaneously. SEO provides long-term organic traffic through educational content targeting trading-related keywords. Paid search campaigns on Google and Bing deliver immediate visibility for high-intent queries like "best forex broker" and "low spread trading." Social media builds brand awareness and community engagement.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Broker Marketing" /><h2>Affiliate and IB Programs</h2><p>Introducing Broker (IB) and affiliate programs are the backbone of forex client acquisition. Structure competitive commission models: CPA for new funded accounts, revenue share on ongoing trading, or hybrid models combining both. Provide affiliates with professional marketing materials, real-time tracking dashboards, and timely payouts to build a loyal partner network.</p><h2>Content and Education</h2><p>Educational content serves dual purposes: SEO authority building and client nurturing. Webinars, market analysis, trading tutorials, and economic calendars position your brand as a trusted authority. Free educational resources attract beginners who, with proper nurturing, become long-term active traders generating consistent revenue.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['marketing', 'client acquisition', 'SEO', 'affiliate marketing', 'CAC', 'advertising'], 7, 'Marketing Strategy for New Forex Broker', 'Marketing strategy for a new forex broker. SEO, affiliates, and targeted advertising.', true, now()),

('forex-broker-operating-costs-budget', 'Forex Broker Operating Costs: Complete Budget', 'Detailed breakdown of monthly operating costs for a forex broker: technology, staff, marketing, and compliance expenses.', '<h2>Fixed Monthly Costs</h2><p>Technology infrastructure forms the largest fixed cost: platform licensing fees ($5,000-$25,000/month depending on the provider), server hosting and colocation ($2,000-$8,000), liquidity provider connectivity ($1,000-$5,000), and CRM/back-office systems ($1,000-$3,000). Office rent, utilities, and basic administration add another $3,000-$15,000 depending on location.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6781273/pexels-photo-6781273.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Operating Costs" /><h2>Personnel Costs</h2><p>A minimum viable team includes compliance officer, dealing desk operator, customer support (2-3 agents), IT administrator, and marketing manager. In mid-range jurisdictions, total salary costs range from $15,000 to $40,000 monthly. As volume grows, add risk management specialists, additional support staff, and account managers for high-value clients.</p><h2>Variable Costs</h2><p>Marketing spend scales with growth targets, typically consuming 30-50% of total budget in the first year. Payment processing fees (1-3% of deposit/withdrawal volume), regulatory reporting costs, and legal consultations represent ongoing variable expenses. Building a 12-month cash reserve covering all fixed costs before launch is strongly recommended.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6781273/pexels-photo-6781273.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['operating costs', 'budget', 'expenses', 'cost optimization', 'forex broker'], 7, 'Forex Broker Operating Costs: Budget', 'Complete budget of forex broker operating costs. Fixed and variable expenses breakdown.', true, now()),

('payment-systems-forex-broker-guide', 'Payment Systems for Forex Brokers: Solutions Overview', 'How to connect and configure payment solutions for a forex broker: bank cards, e-wallets, and cryptocurrency payments.', '<h2>Traditional Payment Methods</h2><p>Bank card processing remains the primary deposit method for most retail traders. Securing a merchant account for forex is challenging due to the high-risk classification. Work with specialized payment service providers (PSPs) who understand the industry. Expect processing fees of 2.5-4.5% and rolling reserves of 5-10% held for chargeback protection.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770775/pexels-photo-6770775.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Payment Systems" /><h2>E-Wallets and Alternative Methods</h2><p>Integrate popular e-wallet solutions like Skrill, Neteller, and local payment methods specific to your target markets. In Southeast Asia, bank transfers and local wallets dominate. In Latin America, PIX and local bank integrations are essential. Each market has preferred payment methods, and supporting them directly impacts your conversion rate.</p><h2>Cryptocurrency Payments</h2><p>Crypto deposits offer advantages including instant processing, lower fees, and accessibility in regions with limited banking infrastructure. Support major cryptocurrencies (BTC, ETH, USDT) through established crypto payment processors. Implement automatic conversion to fiat to avoid exchange rate exposure, and ensure your AML procedures cover crypto transaction monitoring.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770775/pexels-photo-6770775.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['payment systems', 'processing', 'bank cards', 'crypto payments', 'acquiring'], 7, 'Payment Systems for Forex Brokers', 'Overview of payment solutions for forex brokers. Cards, wallets, crypto, and bank transfers.', true, now()),

('hiring-team-new-forex-broker', 'Building a Team for a New Forex Broker: Key Roles', 'What specialists are needed to launch and operate a forex broker: from compliance officer to tech lead.', '<h2>Core Team Structure</h2><p>A minimum viable broker team includes five critical roles: Compliance Officer to manage regulatory requirements and KYC/AML procedures, Dealing Desk Operator for order execution and risk monitoring, IT Administrator for platform maintenance and security, Customer Support Representatives for client-facing operations, and a Marketing Manager for client acquisition strategies.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6694543/pexels-photo-6694543.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Team Building" /><h2>Scaling the Team</h2><p>As the business grows beyond 500 active clients, add specialized roles: Risk Manager to oversee exposure and hedging strategies, Financial Controller for accounting and reporting, Sales Manager to lead the conversion team, and a dedicated Customer Success team for VIP client retention. Technical growth requires backend developers and QA engineers for platform customization.</p><h2>Hiring Strategy</h2><p>Prioritize industry experience for compliance and dealing desk roles where mistakes carry regulatory and financial consequences. For support and marketing, trainable talent with strong communication skills can be more cost-effective. Consider remote hiring for specialized roles to access global talent pools, particularly for compliance experts familiar with your target jurisdictions.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6694543/pexels-photo-6694543.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['team', 'hiring', 'broker', 'compliance', 'recruitment', 'HR'], 7, 'Building a Team for a Forex Broker', 'Key roles needed for launching a forex broker. Minimum team and scaling strategies.', true, now()),

('technical-infrastructure-forex-broker', 'Technical Infrastructure for a Forex Broker', 'Overview of technical components for launching a broker: servers, network architecture, security, and redundancy.', '<h2>Server Architecture</h2><p>A robust broker infrastructure requires multiple server tiers: trading servers for order processing and execution, database servers for client and transaction data, web servers for client-facing applications, and backup servers for disaster recovery. Deploy in Equinix or similar Tier-4 data centers with direct cross-connects to liquidity providers for minimal latency.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6120214/pexels-photo-6120214.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Technical Infrastructure" /><h2>Network and Security</h2><p>Implement enterprise-grade DDoS protection from providers like Cloudflare or Akamai. Use VPN tunnels for all internal communications between servers. Deploy web application firewalls (WAF) to protect client-facing interfaces. SSL/TLS encryption is mandatory for all data in transit, while AES-256 encryption protects data at rest. Regular penetration testing validates security posture.</p><h2>Redundancy and Disaster Recovery</h2><p>Trading operations cannot tolerate downtime. Implement active-passive failover for critical systems with automatic switchover under 60 seconds. Maintain real-time data replication to a geographically separate backup site. Document and regularly test recovery procedures, targeting Recovery Time Objective (RTO) under 4 hours and Recovery Point Objective (RPO) under 5 minutes.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6120214/pexels-photo-6120214.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Starting a Broker', ARRAY['infrastructure', 'servers', 'security', 'data center', 'hosting', 'DDoS'], 8, 'Technical Infrastructure for Forex Broker', 'Server architecture overview for launching a forex broker. Servers, security, and redundancy.', true, now()),

-- Broker Ratings (3)
('verify-forex-broker-reliability', 'How to Verify Forex Broker Reliability', 'Practical guide to checking broker reliability: licenses, financial reports, reviews, and test withdrawals.', '<h2>Regulatory Verification</h2><p>Start by verifying the broker''s license directly on the regulator''s website. Every licensed broker has a registration number searchable on FCA, CySEC, ASIC, or other regulatory databases. Check the license scope to ensure it covers the services offered. Be wary of brokers claiming regulation but not appearing in official registries or listing expired licenses.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6694543/pexels-photo-6694543.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Verify Broker" /><h2>Financial Health Indicators</h2><p>Regulated brokers publish annual financial statements. Review net capital adequacy, client funds segregation practices, and profitability trends. A broker consistently operating at a loss or with declining capital reserves poses elevated counterparty risk. Check if the broker participates in investor compensation schemes that protect client funds in case of insolvency.</p><h2>Practical Testing</h2><p>Before committing significant funds, perform practical tests: open a small account, execute trades during volatile markets to check execution quality, and process a withdrawal to verify speed and smoothness. Monitor slippage rates, requote frequency, and whether the broker honors advertised spreads during news events. These real-world tests reveal more than any marketing material.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6694543/pexels-photo-6694543.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Broker Ratings', ARRAY['broker reliability', 'verification', 'license', 'regulator', 'withdrawals', 'safety'], 7, 'How to Verify Forex Broker Reliability', 'Practical guide to verifying broker reliability. Licenses, reports, and test withdrawals.', true, now()),

('best-brokers-for-scalping-2025', 'Best Brokers for Scalping: Low Spreads and Fast Execution', 'Rating of brokers with the best conditions for scalping: minimal spreads, fast execution, and no restrictions on trading strategies.', '<h2>What Scalpers Need</h2><p>Scalping demands specific broker conditions: raw spreads from 0.0 pips on major pairs, execution speed under 50 milliseconds, no restrictions on trade duration or frequency, and VPS hosting options for algorithmic scalping strategies. ECN/STP brokers typically provide the best environment as they profit from commissions rather than spread markups.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8370752/pexels-photo-8370752.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Scalping Brokers" /><h2>Key Evaluation Criteria</h2><p>Compare brokers on real trading conditions, not advertised ones. Monitor actual spreads during London and New York sessions using independent tools. Test execution speed with market orders during news releases. Verify that the broker''s terms of service explicitly permit scalping and high-frequency strategies without penalties or account restrictions.</p><h2>Infrastructure Considerations</h2><p>For serious scalping, broker proximity to liquidity providers matters. Choose brokers offering free VPS services located in the same data center as their trading servers. Cross-connect latency under 1ms can significantly impact profitability when taking hundreds of small trades daily. Also consider commission structures, as per-lot costs accumulate quickly with high trade frequency.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/8370752/pexels-photo-8370752.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Broker Ratings', ARRAY['scalping', 'low spreads', 'ECN', 'VPS', 'fast execution', 'rating'], 7, 'Best Brokers for Scalping 2025', 'Rating of brokers for scalping. Low spreads, fast execution, and VPS.', true, now()),

('best-broker-for-beginners-guide', 'Best Broker for Beginner Traders', 'How to choose your first forex broker: criteria for beginners, minimum deposit requirements, educational resources, and risk protection.', '<h2>Beginner-Friendly Criteria</h2><p>First-time traders should prioritize four factors: low minimum deposit (ideally under $100), comprehensive educational resources, responsive customer support in their language, and strong regulatory protection including negative balance protection. A quality demo account with realistic market conditions is essential for practicing without financial risk.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Best Broker Beginners" /><h2>Educational Resources and Support</h2><p>The best beginner brokers offer structured learning paths: video tutorials covering platform basics, webinars on fundamental and technical analysis, practice accounts with guided exercises, and glossaries explaining trading terminology. Some brokers provide personal account managers for new clients who guide them through their first trades and help establish proper risk management habits.</p><h2>Common Beginner Mistakes</h2><p>Avoid brokers that aggressively promote high leverage, pressure you to deposit more, or offer unrealistic bonus conditions. Look for transparent fee structures with no hidden charges. Start with a regulated broker even if offshore alternatives offer flashier promotions. The safety of your funds should always outweigh bonus incentives and marketing promises.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Broker Ratings', ARRAY['best broker', 'beginners', 'broker selection', 'demo account', 'education', 'minimum deposit'], 7, 'Best Broker for Beginner Traders', 'How to choose the first forex broker. Criteria for beginners and common mistakes.', true, now()),

-- Cryptocurrency (3)
('crypto-exchange-security-practices', 'Crypto Exchange Security: Best Practices', 'Comprehensive approach to protecting a crypto exchange: from cold storage and multi-signatures to smart contract audits.', '<h2>Multi-Layer Security Architecture</h2><p>Protecting a cryptocurrency exchange requires defense in depth: network-level DDoS mitigation, application-layer web application firewalls, database encryption at rest and in transit, and physical security for hardware security modules. Implement zero-trust networking where every access request is authenticated and authorized regardless of source location.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801648/pexels-photo-6801648.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Crypto Security" /><h2>Asset Custody</h2><p>Store 95% or more of crypto assets in cold storage using air-gapped signing devices and multi-signature schemes requiring 3-of-5 authorized signers. Hot wallets should hold only enough liquidity for immediate withdrawal processing. Implement automated rebalancing between hot and cold wallets based on configurable thresholds and time-of-day patterns.</p><h2>Monitoring and Incident Response</h2><p>Deploy real-time transaction monitoring systems that flag unusual patterns: large withdrawals, rapid sequential transactions, or activity from sanctioned addresses. Establish circuit breakers that automatically pause withdrawals when anomaly scores exceed thresholds. Maintain a documented incident response plan with regular tabletop exercises to ensure team readiness.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801648/pexels-photo-6801648.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Cryptocurrency', ARRAY['security', 'crypto exchange', 'cold storage', 'multi-signature', 'HSM', 'DDoS'], 8, 'Crypto Exchange Security: Best Practices', 'Comprehensive crypto exchange protection. Cold storage, multi-signatures, and monitoring.', true, now()),

('defi-integration-brokerage-platform', 'DeFi Integration in Brokerage Platforms', 'How to integrate DeFi protocols into a brokerage platform: staking, yield farming, and decentralized liquidity pools.', '<h2>DeFi Opportunities for Brokers</h2><p>Decentralized Finance offers brokers new revenue streams and client engagement tools. By integrating DeFi protocols, brokers can offer staking services on Proof-of-Stake networks, access to yield farming strategies through curated vaults, and trading on decentralized exchanges with aggregated liquidity. These features attract crypto-native clients who value transparency and self-custody options.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567443/pexels-photo-7567443.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="DeFi Integration" /><h2>Technical Implementation</h2><p>Integration requires blockchain node infrastructure, smart contract interaction layers, and wallet management systems supporting multiple chains (Ethereum, BSC, Solana, Polygon). Use established DeFi aggregators and SDKs rather than building direct protocol integrations. This reduces development complexity and provides automatic access to new protocols as they launch.</p><h2>Risk Management</h2><p>DeFi carries unique risks: smart contract vulnerabilities, impermanent loss in liquidity pools, protocol governance changes, and blockchain network congestion. Implement clear risk disclosures, position limits, and insurance coverage where available. Educate clients on the differences between CeFi and DeFi risk profiles to set appropriate expectations.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567443/pexels-photo-7567443.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Cryptocurrency', ARRAY['DeFi', 'staking', 'yield farming', 'smart contracts', 'Web3', 'liquidity'], 8, 'DeFi Integration in Brokerage Platform', 'Integrating DeFi protocols into trading platform. Staking, yield farming, and decentralization.', true, now()),

('crypto-payment-processing-broker', 'Crypto Payment Processing for Brokers', 'How to integrate cryptocurrency payment acceptance in a brokerage platform: providers, conversion, and accounting.', '<h2>Choosing a Crypto Payment Provider</h2><p>Select a payment processor based on supported cryptocurrencies (minimum: BTC, ETH, USDT on multiple chains), settlement speed, conversion rates, and compliance tools. Leading providers offer instant conversion to fiat currencies, eliminating exchange rate risk. Compare fee structures carefully: some charge flat per-transaction fees while others take a percentage of the conversion amount.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567444/pexels-photo-7567444.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Crypto Processing" /><h2>Integration and User Experience</h2><p>A seamless deposit experience is critical. Generate unique wallet addresses per client for easy transaction tracking. Support QR code payments for mobile users. Display real-time conversion rates and estimated network fees before the client confirms the deposit. Implement automatic balance crediting once the required number of blockchain confirmations is reached.</p><h2>Compliance Considerations</h2><p>Crypto payments require robust AML monitoring. Use blockchain analytics tools to screen incoming transactions against sanctioned addresses and known illicit wallets. Maintain records linking wallet addresses to verified client identities. Implement transaction monitoring rules that flag unusual patterns such as deposits from mixing services or high-risk jurisdictions.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567444/pexels-photo-7567444.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Cryptocurrency', ARRAY['crypto processing', 'USDT', 'Bitcoin', 'payments', 'conversion', 'AML'], 7, 'Crypto Payment Processing for Brokers', 'Integrating crypto payments into brokerage platform. Providers, AML, and conversion.', true, now()),

-- Prop Trading (2)
('prop-trading-challenge-system', 'Prop Trading Challenge System: Setup and Management', 'How to properly configure challenge programs for prop trading: parameters, phases, automation, and common mistakes.', '<h2>Designing Challenge Parameters</h2><p>A well-designed challenge balances accessibility with risk management. Standard two-phase challenges typically require 8-10% profit target in Phase 1 and 5% in Phase 2, with maximum daily drawdown of 5% and overall drawdown of 10-12%. These parameters attract serious traders while filtering out reckless risk-takers. Offer multiple account sizes from $10K to $200K to capture different market segments.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770775/pexels-photo-6770775.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Prop Trading Challenge" /><h2>Automation and Monitoring</h2><p>Manual challenge evaluation is unsustainable at scale. Implement automated systems that track all challenge rules in real time: drawdown limits, profit targets, minimum trading days, prohibited strategies, and news trading restrictions. Automated notifications alert traders approaching limits, and accounts are automatically failed or passed based on predefined criteria.</p><h2>Common Configuration Mistakes</h2><p>Avoid setting profit targets too high (discourages participation) or drawdown limits too tight (causes excessive failures). Ensure rules are clearly documented and consistently enforced. Hidden restrictions discovered after purchase damage reputation and increase refund demands. Regular analysis of pass rates, average completion time, and funded trader performance helps optimize challenge parameters over time.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770775/pexels-photo-6770775.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Prop Trading', ARRAY['challenge', 'prop trading', 'setup', 'drawdown', 'profit target', 'automation'], 7, 'Prop Trading Challenge System Setup', 'Setting up challenge programs for prop trading. Parameters, phases, and monitoring automation.', true, now()),

('funded-account-model-overview', 'Funded Account Model: Overview and Prospects', 'How the funded account model works in prop trading: profit distribution, scaling, and trader retention strategies.', '<h2>How Funded Accounts Work</h2><p>The funded account model provides traders with company capital after passing evaluation challenges. Traders keep 70-90% of profits while the company retains the rest as compensation for capital risk. This model eliminates the need for traders to risk personal funds while giving prop firms access to diverse trading strategies that generate returns on their capital.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/534216/pexels-photo-534216.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Funded Account" /><h2>Scaling Programs</h2><p>Successful traders want to manage more capital. Implement progressive scaling plans that increase account size by 25% after consistent performance milestones (e.g., 10% profit over 3 months). Top performers can scale from initial $50K accounts to $500K or more. Scaling programs dramatically improve trader retention and create a pipeline of high-performing portfolio managers.</p><h2>Payout and Risk Management</h2><p>Establish clear payout schedules: bi-weekly or monthly withdrawals with minimum thresholds. Implement real-time risk monitoring with automated position liquidation when drawdown limits are breached. Balance trader freedom with portfolio-level risk controls that prevent correlated positions across multiple funded accounts from creating outsized exposure.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/534216/pexels-photo-534216.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Prop Trading', ARRAY['funded account', 'prop trading', 'scaling', 'profit', 'payouts', 'scaling plan'], 7, 'Funded Account Model: Overview', 'How funded accounts work in prop trading. Profit distribution and scaling.', true, now());